Yet, over half (54%) say they would personally see it as morally wrong to have an abortion in unusually difficult circumstances.

‘Impermissible’; ‘Not to have an abortion’ and ‘Not to have one in extremely difficult circumstances’ were grouped for this analysis.

The findings suggest over one-third (37%) of women would be prepared to accept a woman’s right to an abortion in the event of rape or incest.

More than a third believed that women had the right to access abortions if the health of the baby might be severely debilitated if the pregnancy continued (39%), if complicated by fatal foetal conditions (39%), and if the pregnancy is a consequence of the mother being the victim of rape or incest (37%).

A conservative estimate of the willingness to accept a woman’s right to have a termination in specific circumstances are:

35% in the event of rape

37% in the event of fatal foetal conditions, and 39%

57% in the event of severe complication of the health of the baby

Causes of termination of pregnancy

Unintended pregnancy, health of mother and health of infant were ranked most highly in responses (shown in figures below) as the reasons women would choose abortion.
